      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is a constitutional doctrine that protects individuals from arbitrary and unjust laws, ensuring that the government respects fundamental rights and liberties. This principle was notably employed in landmark cases like Roe v. Wade, which protected women's right to privacy and their right to make decisions about their own bodies. Similarly, Loving v. Virginia struck down laws prohibiting interracial marriage, affirming the fundamental right to marry regardless of race. Substantive due process also played a crucial role in Obergefell v. Hodges, which secured the right to same-sex marriage. By establishing these precedents, substantive due process prevents the government from overreaching and intruding into private matters, such as personal relationships, bodily autonomy, and marriage choices, thereby safeguarding individual freedoms against unjust state interference.",
      "source": "target",
